    "discriminators": [
     "The slow frequency sweep IS the category. A siren wails: pitch and brightness climb, reverse and cycle, so spectral_centroid_deviation_hz is very large while the NET spectral_centroid_slope_hz_per_second over the whole file sits near zero. That signed-slope-near-zero-with-huge-deviation pattern separates a cycling siren from a one-way riser or whoosh, which have a large net slope.",
     "Every sibling alarm holds a fixed spectrum: ALARMS-BUZZER and ALARMS-ELECTRONIC lock f0, ALARMS-BELL has fixed partials. None of them sweeps. This is the most distinctive signature in the category.",
     "Mechanical sirens and klaxons only. Police, fire and ambulance sirens go to VEHICLES-SIREN and are acoustically identical, so the name decides.",
     "A klaxon or ahooga that honks on a fixed pitch rather than wailing will look like HORNS-AIR POWERED; the sweep is what should be trusted."
